quran[19]{c,v,t,f}:
38,43,"And We granted to him his family and also the like of them, {1} as a mercy from Us, and as a reminder to people of understanding, {2}",footnotes:1:Traditions show that during this illness everyone except his wife had deserted the Prophet Job (peace be upon him); even his children had turned away. To this Allah has alluded
38,44,"(and We said to him): “Take in your hand a bundle of rushes and strike with it, and do not break your oath.” {1} Indeed We found him steadfast. How excellent a servant (of Ours) he was. Indeed he constantly turned (to his Lord). {2}",footnotes:1:Some jurists hold the view that this concession was specially meant for the Prophet Job (peace be upon him)
38,45,"And remember Our servants � Abraham, Isaac and Jacob � they were endowed with great strength and vision. {1}",footnotes:1:The actual words in the text mean: Those who possessed the hands and the insights. The hand
38,46,"Verily We exalted them in consideration of a sterling quality: their remembrance of the Abode of the Hereafter. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
38,47,"In Our sight they are among the chosen and excellent ones."
38,48,"And remember Ishmael, Elisha, {1} and Dhu al-Kifl. {2} All were of the best.",footnotes:1:Dhul-Kifil also has been mentioned only twice in the Quran
38,49,"This was a remembrance. An excellent retreat awaits the God-fearing"
38,50,"� everlasting Gardens with gates wide open for them {1}",footnotes:1:The words mufattahat-al-lahum-ul-abwab may have several meanings: (1) They will go about in the Gardens (Paradise) freely without any hesitation. (2) No effort will have to be made to open the gates of Paradise
38,51,"wherein they shall recline, wherein they shall ask for abundant fruit and drinks,"
38,52,"and wherein there shall be with them well-matched, bashful mates. {1}",footnotes:1:“Of equal age” may mean that they will be of equal age among themselves
38,53,"All this is what you are promised for the Day of Judgement."
38,54,"This is Our provision for you, never to end."
38,55,"All this (is for the God-fearing). But for the transgressors, an evil resort awaits them �"
38,56,"Hell, where they will be roasted. An evil place to dwell!"
38,57,"All this (is for them); so let them taste boiling water and pus, {1}",footnotes:1:Several meanings of the word ghassaq
38,58,"and other sufferings of the kind."
38,59,"(Observing their followers advancing to Hell they will say, among themselves: “This is a troop rushing in to you. There is no welcome for them. They are destined to roast in the Fire.”"
38,60,"They will reply: “Rather, no welcome to you. (You will roast in Hell.) It is you who led us to this end. What an evil resort!”"
38,61,"They will say: “Our Lord, give twofold punishment in the Fire to him who has led us to this.”"
